onate to wikipediawikipedia store interaction helpabout wikipediacommunity portalrecent changescontact page tools what links hererelated changesupload filespecial pagespermanent linkpage informationwikidata itemcite this page printexport create a bookdownload as pdfprintable version languages deutschespañolفارسیfrançais한국어português edit links this page was last edited on  july  at  text is available under the creative commons attributionsharealike license additional terms may apply by using this site you agree to the terms of use and privacy policy wikipedia® is a registered trademark of the wikimedia foundation inc a nonprofit organization privacy policy about wikipedia disclaimers contact wikipedia developers cookie statement mobile view shaw communications  wikipedia shaw communications from wikipedia the free encyclopedia jump to navigation search shaw communications inc type public traded as tsxv sjra voting tsx sjrb nonvoting nyse sjr nonvoting industry telecommunications founded  in edmonton alberta canada headquarters calgary alberta canada key people jr shaw executive chairman jim shaw vice chairman bradley s shaw ceo jay mehr president paul mcaleese coo freedom mobile products cable television high speed internet telephone direct broadcast satellite network and specialty broadcasting logistics tracking radio revenue cad  billion  operating income cad  billion  net income cad  million  number of employees   divisions shaw broadcast services shaw direct subsidiaries freedom mobile website wwwshawca shaw communications logo used from  to  shaw communications logo used from  to  shaw communications inc is a canadian telecommunications company which provides telephone internet television and mobile services all backed by a fibre optic network headquartered in calgary alberta shaw provides services mostly in british columbia and alberta with smaller systems in saskatchewan manitoba and northern ontario through its subsidiary freedom mobile shaw provides mobile services in urban areas of british columbia alberta and southern ontario the companys chief competitor is telus corporation contents  history  return to broadcasting  –present  freedom mobile divestment of media assets  other activities  controversy  internet usagebased billing  complaints  eponymous buildings  gallery  see also  notes  external links historyedit shaw was founded as capital cable television company ltd in edmonton alberta in  the company changed its name to shaw cablesystems ltd and went public on the tsx in  the company grew during the s and s through acquisitions of firms including classicomm in the toronto area access communications in nova scotia fundy cable in new brunswick trillium cable in ontario telecable in saskatchewan greater winnipeg cablevision serving areas east of the red river and videon cablesystems of winnipeg serving areas west of the red river which had itself previously acquired vidéotrons assets in alberta however two swaps in  and  with rogers cable have resulted in its assets being restricted to western canada and a few areas of northern ontario in  shaw spun out its media properties into a second publiclytraded company corus entertainment prior to  shaw owned cable systems in the united states previously owned by moffat communications serving six communities in florida eastern pasco county clermont palm coast ormond beach west palm beach and doral and the houston texas suburbs of kingwood lake conroe and lake livingston in february  the florida systems would be sold to time warner cable with the west palm beach and doral systems later sold to comcast and the other systems spun off to bright house networks while the texas systems were sold to cequel iii as part of its thencebridge connections subsidiary now suddenlink communications in  shaw entered the aws spectrum auction with the intention of possibly becoming a wireless phone provider the auction ended july  giving shaw communications enough spectrum to build a wireless network in its home provinces of british columbia alberta saskatchewan manitoba and ontario this spectrum ultimately went unused and was sold to rogers communications in january  in july  shaw announced its acquisition of mountain cablevision in september rogers sued shaw to block the sale citing violations of a noncompete clause however the suit was quickly dismissed by the ontario superior court the purchase was approved by the crtc on october   the acquisition was shaws first cable property east of sault ste marie since the  swaps with rogers and cogeco shaws reentry into southern ontario would be shortlived as its hamilton system would be resold to rogers in january  as part of a deal which also saw unused wireless spectrum sold to the company and saw rogers sell its stake in specialty channel tvtropolis return to broadcastingedit on april   shaw announced a deal to acquire three television stations — chwitv in windsor ontario cknxtv in wingham ontario and ckxtv in brandon manitoba — from ctvglobemedia ctv had indicated that it would shut down the stations all of which were incurring extensive financial losses later in the year if a buyer could not be found and had placed them on the market at a price of just  each however it was reported on june   that shaw has backed out of the deal and is declining to complete the purchase chwitv would remain on the air as is cknxtv would become a repeater of london station cfpltv in september  while ckxtv would close down entirely in october  in february  shaw announced an agreement with the financially troubled canwest whereby shaw would buy an  voting interest and  equity interest in the restructured entity of canwest pending approvals from the crtc and others three months later following negotiations with rival bidders the company said it would purchase the entirety of canwests broadcasting assets including the interests in the cw media subsidiary partially held by goldman sachs capital partners canwests newspapers were not part of the shaw deal and were sold separately to postmedia network the acquisition was completed on october   after crtc approval for the sale was announced on october  forming the shaw media division –presentedit in november  shaw underwent a corporate rebranding introducing an updated logo and slogan along with a new promotional campaign featuring animated robots including two named mascot robots bit and bud that live in a representation of shaws infrastructure depicting them as being responsible for how their services work the campaign was designed by the vancouverbased agency rethink who were also responsible for bell canadas beaver characters frank and gordon in april  shaw business solutions took over enmaxs envision subsidiary which had built a fiberoptic network throughout calgary the acquisition was completed for  million shaw communications logo used  to current in  shaw partnered with rogers communications to launch shomi a subscription video on demand service in february  shaw communications announced that they would close operations for service call centers in edmonton calgary and kelowna and consolidate operations in victoria vancouver winnipeg and montreal  of shaws  employees were affected by the consolidation and cuts the company offered affected employees the option to relocate to its centralized offices apply for a new job at their location or leave the company with a severance package for former employees unable to relocate in  shaw attempted to begin developing an iptvbased platform for its television services however after experiencing issues developing the platform shaw took a  million writedown in june  and announced that it was licensing comcasts cloudbased x architecture in january  shaw launched its mobile television app freerange tv based on x infrastructure which allows shaw subscribers to stream selected tv channels and ondemand content freedom mobile divestment of media assetsedit on december   shaw announced its proposed acquisition of independent wireless provider wind mobile from its investors in a deal worth approximately  billion the transaction closed on march   under shaw the company was renamed freedom mobile in november  coinciding with the launch of its g lte network the acquisition of wind was funded by a reorganization in april  which saw the shaw media unit transferred to corus entertainment in exchange for  billion in cash and  class b nonvoting shares of corus the sale did not include shaws  stake in the shomi streaming service and cjbntv kenora shomi was shut down in november  and cjbntv kenora was shut down in january  on january   shaw announced the launch of bluesky—a new iptvbased television service based on comcasts x platform the service was initially made available in calgary other activitiesedit shaw is the parent of shaw broadcast services previously shaw satellite services canadian satellite communications or cancom and through shaw broadcast services shaw direct one of canadas two national direct broadcast satellite providers for many years it also owned a number of radio stations and specialty television services these assets were later spun off into corus entertainment in an effort to satisfy a nowrepealed crtc policy discouraging crossownership of cablesystems and specialty services controversyedit internet usagebased billingedit in december  shaw filed complaints with the crtc to have competing internet video services such as netflix classified as broadcasters under canadian law in the same month shaw introduced usage based billing on internet plans and lowered plan caps an average of  while introducing overage fees of  to  per gigabyte on february   shaw agreed to put a hold on usage based billing for its services and to this date continues to not charge customers any overages for surpassing internet data caps complaintsedit customer service complaints are frequent among canadian cable mobile and internet users eponymous buildingsedit shaw barlow calgary shaw centre saskatoon shaw centre ottawa shaw park winnipeg shaw conference centre edmonton shaw court calgary head office shaw tower vancouver shaw ocean discovery centre  notforprofit cultural and learning centre sponsored by shaw communications sidney bc galleryedit shaw communications barlow office and call centre in calgary shaw conference centre edmonton shaw technician van with the previous logo see alsoedit companies portal burning log tv program canwest classicomm cybertipca list of assets owned by shaw communications media ownership in canada shaw tv telecom notesedit  a b c d shaw senior leadership shaw communications inc retrieved march     hardy ian april   alek krstajic is stepping down as ceo of freedom mobile mobilesyrup retrieved july     company profile for shaw communications inc sjr retrieved    shaw history shaw communications inc  retrieved    shaw cablesystems receives approval from crtc to purchase greater winnipeg cablevision canadian radio and telecommunications commission  retrieved    milestones shawca retrieved    canuck players plan splitting up of wic variety retrieved  march    corus lines up behind canuck shaws assets variety retrieved  march    pasco time warner to expand with shaw purchase retrieved  july    cequel iii to buy shaws texas systems ced retrieved  july    post financial  wireless spectrum auction canadacom retrieved    a b shaw hangs up on its cellular plans the globe and mail january   retrieved  january    rogers sues to block shaws ontario cable buy cbc news retrieved  march    rogers territorial lawsuit against shaw quashed cbc news retrieved  march    shaw communications press release shaw closes mountain cablevision transaction pdf october     shaw communications gets crtc approval to buy mountain cablevision in hamilton canadian press ottawa canadaeastcom october     ctv accepts shaw offer to buy local stations ctvglobemedia press release via trademarkets april    grant robertson shaw cancels deal for  ctv stations the